<section class="bg-deep py-20 md:py-24">
  <div class="max-w-4xl mx-auto px-4 sm:px-6 lg:px-8">

    <div class="max-w-2xl mb-12 reveal">
      <span class="amber-rule"></span>
      <h2 style="font-size:clamp(1.8rem,3.5vw,2.7rem);font-weight:700;color:#fff;margin-bottom:.75rem;">
        Frequently Asked Questions
      </h2>
      <p style="color:#64748b;font-size:.9rem;line-height:1.75;">
        Common planning questions for high-net-worth individuals establishing Miami as their financial and legal home. Educational overviews only—not legal or tax advice.
      </p>
    </div>

    <div style="display:flex;flex-direction:column;gap:.75rem;">

      <!-- FAQ 1 -->
      <details class="reveal">
        <summary>
          <span style="font-family:'Cormorant Garamond',serif;font-size:1.15rem;font-weight:600;color:#e2e8f0;line-height:1.3;">How do I legally establish Florida domicile while maintaining business interests in the North?</span>
          <svg class="faq-icon w-5 h-5" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2.5" viewBox="0 0 24 24"><path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" d="M12 4.5v15m7.5-7.5h-15"/></svg>
        </summary>
        <div class="faq-body">
          <p style="margin-bottom:.9rem;">Maintaining active business interests in New York, Connecticut, or Massachusetts while claiming Florida domicile is one of the most legally complex—and most commonly audited—scenarios in interstate tax planning. The key distinction is between "domicile" (your permanent home, a singular and intentional concept) and "residence" (where you physically spend time). A person can have only one domicile but multiple residences.</p>
          <p style="margin-bottom:.9rem;"><strong style="color:#cbd5e1;">The New York Audit Threat:</strong> New York's Department of Taxation and Finance is widely regarded as the most aggressive state revenue authority in the country for domicile audits. New York applies a six-factor "domicile test" examining: (1) the relative size and value of your homes; (2) time spent in each location; (3) location of "near and dear" items (family heirlooms, artwork, jewelry); (4) business connections; (5) location of family and social contacts; and (6) jurisdiction of professional services. Passing this audit requires genuine, documented life change—not merely cosmetic relocation.</p>
          <p style="margin-bottom:.9rem;"><strong style="color:#cbd5e1;">Practical Steps for Business Owners:</strong> If you operate a business with a New York office, the income attributable to New York workdays may still be taxable to New York regardless of your domicile—this is "source income" taxation. Restructuring compensation, board meeting locations, and business activity documentation can reduce this exposure, but it cannot be eliminated entirely if you are genuinely performing work in New York. Engage a CPA and tax attorney experienced in New York non-resident allocations.</p>
          <p style="margin-bottom:.9rem;"><strong style="color:#cbd5e1;">Affirmative Florida Documentation:</strong> File the Florida Declaration of Domicile. Obtain a Florida voter registration card, driver's license, and vehicle registration. Establish your primary banking relationship in Florida. Move your primary physician, attorney, and accountant relationships to Florida-based professionals. Ensure your Florida home is materially larger, more expensive, or more personally significant than any retained Northern property. Keep diary logs and receipts documenting Florida presence throughout the year.</p>
          <p style="color:#64748b;">The most common audit-trigger: maintaining a New York apartment of comparable or greater value to your Florida home while spending significant time in the city. If you own a $4M Brickell condo and a $3.5M Manhattan co-op, New York will scrutinize every factor. The Florida home must be demonstrably your primary habitation. Consult a qualified domicile transition attorney before the tax year in which you intend the change to take effect.</p>
        </div>
      </details>

      <!-- FAQ 2 -->
      <details class="reveal">
        <summary>
          <span style="font-family:'Cormorant Garamond',serif;font-size:1.15rem;font-weight:600;color:#e2e8f0;line-height:1.3;">How do Florida's fiduciary laws apply to digital and crypto assets in estates and trusts?</span>
          <svg class="faq-icon w-5 h-5" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2.5" viewBox="0 0 24 24"><path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" d="M12 4.5v15m7.5-7.5h-15"/></svg>
        </summary>
        <div class="faq-body">
          <p style="margin-bottom:.9rem;">Florida enacted the Florida Fiduciary Access to Digital Assets Act (§740.001 et seq., Florida Statutes), based on the Revised Uniform Fiduciary Access to Digital Assets Act (RUFADAA). This legislation addresses the legal authority of fiduciaries—including trustees, executors, and agents under power of attorney—to access, manage, and transfer digital assets, including cryptocurrency holdings.</p>
          <p style="margin-bottom:.9rem;"><strong style="color:#cbd5e1;">What "Digital Assets" Are Covered:</strong> The Florida statute covers electronic records in which an individual has a right or interest, including cryptocurrency wallets, NFTs, digital exchange accounts, online financial accounts, and even social media accounts with monetary value. The statute creates a priority hierarchy: (1) an online tool (like a legacy contact designation on a platform) supersedes; (2) a specific provision in a will, trust, or power of attorney controls; (3) in the absence of both, platform terms of service govern.</p>
          <p style="margin-bottom:.9rem;"><strong style="color:#cbd5e1;">Critical Planning Gaps for Crypto Holders:</strong> Most custodial crypto exchange accounts (Coinbase, Kraken, Gemini) have terms of service that restrict account transfer—meaning they may not honor a trustee's or executor's claim without specific legal documentation and platform cooperation. Self-custied assets (hardware wallets, cold storage with private keys) present a different and arguably greater risk: if the private key is lost or inaccessible upon death or incapacity, the assets may be permanently unrecoverable regardless of Florida law.</p>
          <p style="margin-bottom:.9rem;"><strong style="color:#cbd5e1;">Best Practices for Florida Residents with Significant Digital Assets:</strong> Prepare a separate, secured "Digital Asset Memorandum" (not part of the public will) that catalogs wallet addresses, exchange accounts, custody solutions, and access protocols. Reference this document in your trust or power of attorney. Consider a professional digital asset custodian or a qualified digital asset trust structure. Ensure your trustee or executor has the technical literacy—or access to technical counsel—to manage these assets.</p>
          <p style="color:#64748b;">The valuation of crypto assets at death for estate tax purposes follows IRS Revenue Ruling 2023-14 (treating crypto as property), using fair market value on the date of death. For large crypto estates, qualified appraisers experienced in digital asset valuation should be engaged. This area of law is evolving rapidly—Florida-specific digital asset counsel is essential for any portfolio with meaningful crypto exposure.</p>
        </div>
      </details>

      <!-- FAQ 3 -->
      <details class="reveal">
        <summary>
          <span style="font-family:'Cormorant Garamond',serif;font-size:1.15rem;font-weight:600;color:#e2e8f0;line-height:1.3;">How do Florida Domestic Asset Protection Trusts (DAPTs) work in practice?</span>
          <svg class="faq-icon w-5 h-5" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2.5" viewBox="0 0 24 24"><path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" d="M12 4.5v15m7.5-7.5h-15"/></svg>
        </summary>
        <div class="faq-body">
          <p style="margin-bottom:.9rem;">Florida's Domestic Asset Protection Trust statute (§736.0505, Florida Statutes) allows a settlor—the person who creates and funds the trust—to be a permissible discretionary beneficiary of an irrevocable trust while the assets held within it receive protection from future creditors. This is a departure from the traditional common law rule that a settlor could not protect assets transferred to a trust in which the settlor retained a beneficial interest.</p>
          <p style="margin-bottom:.9rem;"><strong style="color:#cbd5e1;">Structural Requirements for a Florida DAPT:</strong> The trust must be: (1) an irrevocable trust; (2) established under Florida law with a Florida trustee (individual or institutional); (3) funded with a genuine transfer—not merely a fraudulent conveyance; and (4) the settlor's interest must be discretionary, not mandatory. The trustee must have the independent authority to make distribution decisions. If a court finds the settlor retains too much control, the protection may be pierced.</p>
          <p style="margin-bottom:.9rem;"><strong style="color:#cbd5e1;">The Four-Year Look-Back:</strong> Florida's statute imposes a four-year statute of limitations (or one year from when the creditor discovered or should have discovered the transfer, if later) for a creditor to challenge a DAPT transfer as fraudulent. This means a DAPT funded today does not provide full protection until four years have elapsed without a creditor claim. Transferring assets to a DAPT when litigation is already imminent or anticipated is likely a fraudulent transfer and provides no protection.</p>
          <p style="margin-bottom:.9rem;"><strong style="color:#cbd5e1;">Practical Use Cases:</strong> Florida DAPTs are commonly used by physicians, attorneys, real estate developers, and business owners who face professional liability exposure and wish to protect wealth accumulated prior to future claims. When layered with the Florida homestead exemption, the combination creates a two-tier shield: the primary residence protected by constitutional homestead, and investment and liquid assets protected within the DAPT structure.</p>
          <p style="color:#64748b;"><strong style="color:#cbd5e1;">Interstate Comity Concern:</strong> One complexity: if a creditor obtains a judgment in a non-Florida court (say, New York), the Full Faith and Credit Clause of the U.S. Constitution may require that judgment to be honored in Florida—potentially undermining the DAPT protection. The enforceability of DAPT protections against out-of-state judgments remains an active area of litigation and legal scholarship. A Florida estate planning attorney specializing in asset protection is essential for any DAPT implementation.</p>
        </div>
      </details>

    </div>
  </div>
</section>

